issue_body:
Hi,
    The issue can be illustrated as follows:

	#include <algorithm>

	namespace dlib
	{
		struct matrix_exp {};

		template<typename T, int n = 2>
		struct matrix : matrix_exp {
			operator T() const {
				static_assert(n == 1);
			}
		};
		void clamp(matrix_exp&, matrix_exp&, matrix_exp&) {}
	}

	// test\matrix2.cpp

	using namespace dlib;
	using namespace std;

	void f()
	{
		matrix<int> x, l, u;
		// std::clamp is added in C++17 and chosen by the overload resolution because it is an exact match.
		// To resolve 'operator <', the compiler is required to instantiate matrix<int>::operator int
		// Then the assertion in it will be hit
		clamp(x, l, u);
	}

One possible way to workaround this in the test is to use 'dlib::clamp' explicitly.

I'm currently working on a bad word detector bot. It is supposed to add the 😡 emoji as a reaction to messages containing "bad" words. the client.add_reaction bit, however, does absolutely nothing; it doesn't even return a error!
code snippet;
`@client.event
async def on_message(message):
    if scan(message.content):
        client.add_reaction(message, "\N{POUTING FACE}")
        print("detected")
    else:
        print("safe")`

Fix was already added in commits d9bbf7c905ec91f5c852acbbdc2b4c9313c9aad6 and 8d2c1e73720a20cadfab45e42a66a39e5bf06620, but this might not be enough.

In upstream cefclient there is a 0.05 sec sleep before each call to message loop work, so that CEF has time to process it. Looks like we also need to add it in CEF Python. I thought CefDoMessageLoopWork() was blocking, but if the sleep is required, then it means that it executes asynchronously and returns immediately.

```
  // We need to run the message pump until it is idle. However we don't have
  // that information here so we run the message loop "for a while".
  for (int i = 0; i < 10; ++i) {
    // Do some work.
    CefDoMessageLoopWork();

    // Sleep to allow the CEF proc to do work.
    usleep(50000);
  }
```

In discussion [2] Marshall states that this will hopefully be fixed as part of Issue 1805 (external message pump). So if message loop work is implemented using external pump maybe this fix won't be required any more - needs testing.

