The connection types are filled with assertions that the target type is a non-abstract subclass of `Node` ("`ObjectTypes in a edge have to be Nodes`"). But `Node` itself *should* be perfectly valid. It allows you to create general connections to multiple `Node` subtypes which can be expanded with fragments.

For example:

```graphql
type Foo implements Node {
  id: ID!
  myFoo: String!
}
type Bar implements Node {
  id: ID!
  myBar: String!
}
type NodeEdge {
  node: Node
  cursor: String!
}
type NodeConnection {
  pageInfo: PageInfo!
  edges: [NodeEdge]
}
type Viewer {
  foosAndBars: NodeConnection
}
type Query {
  node(id: ID!): Node
  viewer: Viewer!
}
```

Queried via:
```graphql
query {
  viewer {
    myFoosAndBars {
      edges {
        node {
          id
          ...on Foo {
            myFoo
          }
          ...on Bar {
            myBar
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Hello,

When I do a mutation, I want to be able to return the type directly instead of wrapping it into another field:

So, I want to do:
```
mutation {
  createPerson {
    __typename // <-- this should give you 'PersonType', ideally
    id
    firstName
    lastName
  }
}
```

but it seems like in Graphene Django, you have to wrap it inside another field:

```
mutation {
  createPerson {
    __typename // <-- in reality, this does not give you 'PersonType'
    person {
      __typename // <-- this gives you 'PersonType'
      id
      firstName
      lastName
    }
  }
}
```

How can I achieve the former?

This is a common pattern. Even the official documentation has this pattern: http://graphql.org/learn/queries/#mutations

Hi, i noticed that current version of pybind11 evaluate C++ function default arguments only once during 'binding phase' (Python style) as opposed to do so for every-call as C++ does. While this behavior certainly inline with Python idioms it might be not desirable while dealing with C++ code and might lead to confusing situation when 'same' call from Python and from C++ will lead to different results (example below). Also: some C++ function default might be written in a way that does not allow it to be called before certain init() was called (which is impossible with current implementation).

So, would it be possible to make functions default for binded functions to be evaluated during function call?

Thanks,

```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>

int foo_default()
{
  std::cout << "Default called!!!" << std::endl;
  static int a=0;
  return a++;
}

int foo(int a = foo_default())
{
	return a;
}

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");

	m.def("foo", (int (*)(int)) &foo, "doc", pybind11::arg_t<int>("a", foo_default(), "foo_default()"));

    return m.ptr();
}
```

#### Issue description

If a member function being wrapped by `py::class_::def` is actually implemented in a base class, then calling the member fails.

In the example code, it gives
```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "./testit.py", line 6, in <module>
    b.do_nothing()
TypeError: do_nothing(): incompatible function arguments. The following argument types are supported:
    1. (self: A) -> None

Invoked with: <pbtest._pbtest.B object at 0x7f1a691c3810>
```

This is presumably because the type of &B::do_nothing is actually `void (A::*)()` rather than `void (B::*)()`. While it can be fixed by explicitly casting it, it seems like it should be possible for pybind11 to fix this itself, since it knows at compile time which class is being wrapped.

#### Reproducible example code

C++:
```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

class A
{
public:
    void do_nothing() {}
};

class B : public A
{
public:
    using A::A;
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(_pbtest)
{
    py::module m("_pbtest");

    py::class_<B>(m, "B")
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("do_nothing", &B::do_nothing);

    return m.ptr();
}
```

Python:
```python
from pbtest._pbtest import B

b = B()
b.do_nothing()
```

Related to #19 

I've implemented a reader-writer lock (following https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Readers%E2%80%93writer_lock#Implementation) for my own needs.

```python
@attr.s(slots=True)
class ReadLockManager:

    rwlock = attr.ib()

    async def __aenter__(self):
        async with self.rwlock.r:
            self.rwlock.b += 1
            if self.rwlock.b == 1:
                await self.rwlock.g.acquire()
                # Don't worry, I known what I'm doing...
                self.rwlock.g._owner = 42

    async def __aexit__(self, *args):
        async with self.rwlock.r:
            self.rwlock.b -= 1
            if self.rwlock.b == 0:
                # Don't worry, I known what I'm doing...
                self.rwlock.g._owner = trio._core.current_task()
                self.rwlock.g.release()


@attr.s(slots=True)
class WriteLockManager:

    rwlock = attr.ib()

    async def __aenter__(self):
        await self.rwlock.g.acquire()

    async def __aexit__(self, *args):
        self.rwlock.g.release()


@attr.s(slots=True)
class RWLock:
    r = attr.ib(default=attr.Factory(trio.Lock))
    g = attr.ib(default=attr.Factory(trio.Lock))
    b = attr.ib(default=0)

    def acquire_read(self):
        return ReadLockManager(self)

    def acquire_write(self):
        return WriteLockManager(self)
```

The codebase is really straightforward, except for the fact the `g` lock is released from a different coroutine that it was acquired in the first place. This obliged me to hack the `g._owner` field...

This make me wonder if it wouldn't be better to have this kind part of trio directly (given no normal user should be expected to use this kind of hack on a 3rd party dependency). Beside it's a fairly common kind of lock so DRY should apply here.
